# Qwen3-0.6B quantized generation on Emily

```elixir
Mix.install(
  [
    {:emily, "~> 0.1"},
    {:bumblebee,
     github: "elixir-nx/bumblebee", ref: "273805e95507dc7866b958d90e0012a3abad1761"},
    {:tokenizers, "~> 0.5"},
    {:nx, "~> 0.10"},
    {:axon, "~> 0.7"},
    {:kino, "~> 0.14"}
  ],
  config: [
    nx: [default_backend: Emily.Backend]
  ]
)
```

## Overview

This notebook loads `Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B` through Bumblebee, quantizes
every dense layer's kernel to int4 via MLX affine group-wise
quantization, and greedy-decodes a completion. It also demonstrates
`Emily.Stream` for concurrent serving on a shared model.

The checkpoint is ~1.5 GB on first fetch. Budget several minutes for
the cold run.

## Dense baseline

```elixir
{:ok, %{model: model, params: params, spec: spec}} =
  Bumblebee.load_model({:hf, "Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B"})

{:ok, tokenizer} = Bumblebee.load_tokenizer({:hf, "Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B"})
{:ok, generation_config} = Bumblebee.load_generation_config({:hf, "Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B"})

model_info = %{model: model, params: params, spec: spec}

config =
  Bumblebee.configure(generation_config,
    max_new_tokens: 32,
    strategy: %{type: :greedy_search}
  )

serving =
  Bumblebee.Text.generation(model_info, tokenizer, config,
    defn_options: [compiler: Emily.Compiler]
  )

%{results: [%{text: dense_text}]} =
  Nx.Serving.run(serving, "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.")

dense_text
```

## Quantization transform

Rewriting the Axon graph so every `:dense` node runs
`Emily.Quantization.Layers.quantized_dense/4` needs Axon, which is
test-only in the Emily package. For the notebook we inline the
transform using `Axon.map_nodes/2`. A production-grade version lives
in the Emily test suite at `test/support/quantization_transform.ex`.

```elixir
defmodule DenseTransform do
  alias Emily.Quantization.Layers
  alias Emily.QuantizedWeight

  @default_opts [bits: 4, group_size: 128, transpose: true]

  def quantize(model, params, opts \\ []) do
    opts = Keyword.merge(@default_opts, opts)
    {quantize_graph(model, opts), quantize_params(model, params, opts)}
  end

  defp quantize_graph(model, opts) do
    Axon.map_nodes(model, fn
      %Axon.Node{op: :dense} = node -> dense_to_quantized(node, opts)
      other -> other
    end)
  end

  defp dense_to_quantized(%Axon.Node{} = node, opts) do
    # Replace the :dense op with a :quantized_dense Axon node that
    # invokes Emily.Quantization.Layers.quantized_dense/4 during the
    # forward pass. The kernel parameter shape is preserved at graph
    # time; the quantized body ships in the params map.
    %Axon.Node{
      node
      | op: Layers,
        op_name: :quantized_dense,
        args:
          node.args ++
            [bits: opts[:bits], group_size: opts[:group_size], transpose: opts[:transpose]]
    }
  end

  defp quantize_params(model, params, opts) do
    # Walk the param tree. For every kernel tied to a dense layer in
    # `model`, replace the f32 tensor with %QuantizedWeight{}.
    dense_layer_names =
      model
      |> Axon.properties()
      |> Map.get(:names, [])
      |> Enum.filter(fn name -> is_dense?(model, name) end)
      |> MapSet.new()

    update_in(params.data, fn data ->
      Map.new(data, fn
        {name, %{"kernel" => kernel} = layer_params} ->
          if MapSet.member?(dense_layer_names, name) do
            qw = QuantizedWeight.from_dense(kernel, opts)
            {name, %{layer_params | "kernel" => qw}}
          else
            {name, layer_params}
          end

        other ->
          other
      end)
    end)
  end

  defp is_dense?(model, _layer_name) do
    # Simplified: in a real loader, walk model.nodes and check
    # :op == :dense. See test/support/quantization_transform.ex for a
    # production-grade version.
    true
  end
end
```

> **In practice**, use
> `Emily.Quantization.Transform.quantize/3` from the Emily test
> support tree — it handles the edge cases this inlined version
> glosses over (layer-name skipping, dtype coercion, the
> `:except` option). It lives under `test/support/` because Axon
> is an `only: :test` dep on Emily.

## Quantized inference

```elixir
{qmodel, qparams} =
  DenseTransform.quantize(model, params,
    bits: 4,
    group_size: 128,
    transpose: true
  )

qmodel_info = %{model: qmodel, params: qparams, spec: spec}

qserving =
  Bumblebee.Text.generation(qmodel_info, tokenizer, config,
    defn_options: [compiler: Emily.Compiler]
  )

%{results: [%{text: quant_text}]} =
  Nx.Serving.run(qserving, "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.")

quant_text
```

The quantized output will drift from the dense baseline — int4 noise
across every linear is expected. The test at
`test/emily/conformance/qwen3_quant_full_test.exs` pins a
deterministic reference string for regression-testing the
quantization stack.

## Concurrent serving via `Emily.Stream`

For concurrent inference on a shared model, each serving worker
should own its own MLX command queue. `Emily.Stream.with_stream/2`
does that per-process:

```elixir
stream = Emily.Stream.new(:gpu)

task1 =
  Task.async(fn ->
    Emily.Stream.with_stream(stream, fn ->
      Nx.Serving.run(qserving, "Question 1?")
    end)
  end)

task2 =
  Task.async(fn ->
    Emily.Stream.with_stream(Emily.Stream.new(:gpu), fn ->
      Nx.Serving.run(qserving, "Question 2?")
    end)
  end)

{Task.await(task1, :infinity), Task.await(task2, :infinity)}
```

Each `Emily.Stream` maps to its own Metal command queue. Weights are
shared across streams — no duplication — so the memory cost of adding
a stream is the Metal command buffer, not the model.

Create streams once at worker init, not per-request.
